tion laborers throughout the Caribbean, their relocation would provide whites with a monopoly over the benefits of settling indigenous land in temperate zones throughout North America. At the same time, black activists and intellectuals contested these geographic-based controls by developing alternative discourses on race and the environment. By tracing these negotiations of the transnational racialization of freedom, Asaka demonstrates the importance of considering settler colonialism and black freedom together while complicating the prevailing frames through which the intertwined histories of British and U.S. emancipation and colonialism have been understood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlack peoplexColonizationzTropics. 0aBlacksxColonizationxTropics. 0aBlacksxColonizationzTropics. 0aEnslaved personsxEmancipation. 0aFree Black people. 0aFree blacks. 0aRace relationsxHistoryx18th century. 0aRace relationsxHistoryx19th century. 0aRace relationsxHistoryy18th century. 0aRace relationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxEmancipation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372752/original  a978-3-11-069634-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles